04727nam a22006375i 9780814786161DE-B159720220329044247.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220329t19921992nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808147861617 a10.18574/nyu/97808147861612doi  a(DE-B1597)548571  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aE169.12b.B53 1992eb 7aHIS0360602bisacsh04a973.92221 aBiel, Steven, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aIndependent Intellectuals in the United States, 1910-1945 /cSteven Biel. 1aNew York, NY : bNew York University Press, c[1992] 4cÂ©1992  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aThe American Social Experience ;v100tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1. The Repudiation of the University -- t2. Making a Living -- t3. From Expression to Influence -- t4. The Geography of the Intellectual Life -- t5. Women and the Critical Community -- t6. Education and the New Basis for Community -- t7. An Alternative Morality -- t8. Uses of the Past -- t9. Versions of Marx -- tEpilogue: Defending the Intellectual Life -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aA new intellectual community came together in the United States in the 1910s and 1920s, a community outside the universities, the professions and, in general, the established centers of intellectual life. A generation of young intellectuals was increasingly challenging both the genteel tradition and the growing division of intellectual labor. Adversarial and anti-professional, they exhibited a hostility to boundaries and specialization that compelled them toward an ambitious and self-conscious generalism and made them a force in the American political, literary, and artistic landscape. This book is a cultural history of this community of free-lance critics and an exploration of their collective effort to construct a viable public intellectual life in America. Steven Biel illustrates the diversity of the body of writings produced by these critics, whose subjects ranged from literature and fine arts to politics, economics, history, urban planning, and national character. Conceding that significant differences and conflicts did exist in the works of individual thinkers, Biel nonetheless maintains that a broader picture of this vibrant culture has been obscured by attempts to classify intellectuals according to political or ideological persuasions. His book brings to life the ways in which this community sought out alternative ways of making a living, devised strategies for reaching and engaging the public, debated the involvement of women in the intellectual community and incorporated Marxism into its evolving search for a decisive intellectual presence in American life. Examined in this lively study are the role and contributions of such figures as Randolph Bourne, Max Eastman, Crystal Eastman, Walter Lippmann, Margaret Sanger, Van Wyck Brooks, Floyd Dell, Edmund Wilson, Mable Dodge, Paul Rosenfeld, H. L. Mencken, Lewis Mumford, Malcolm Cowley, Matthew Josephson, John Reed, Waldo Frank, Gilbert Seldes, and Harold Stearns.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mrz 2022) 0aIntellectualszUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 7aHISTORY / United States / 20th Century.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNew York University Press Archive eBook-Package Pre-2000z978311071692440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780814786161423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780814786161/original  a978-3-11-071692-4  New York University Press Archive eBook-Package Pre-2000b2000  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHAL